@NODE "Mail_37" " Re: can anyone explain this problem? "
From: Ralf Berkvens <ralf@ilse.nl>
Date: 10-26-00 07:32:21
Subject: @{b}Re: can anyone explain this problem?@{ub}

> Now, given I want to poke BEFORE I peek, I have the address and want to peek
> at the "new" data resulting from the poke.
> 
> If, I write a program to poke the data then I run this bit of code, it
> works.  However if I remove the remarked lines at the top (tried two ways)
> I get a message:
(can't read the attached code here, :( )
> 
> guru - line 1111 emulator

are you using a machine with memory caching ability (amiga 1200 or better)?

this could cause the data you have poked to only be poked to the cache, and the
peek may interfere with the process in some strange way. Perhaps you can 
turn off the caching?

Ralf


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_38" " Re: can anyone explain this problem? "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 10-26-00 10:46:18
Subject: @{b}Re: can anyone explain this problem?@{ub}

Hi Andrew

> If, I write a program to poke the data then I run this bit of code, it
> works.  However if I remove the remarked lines at the top (tried two ways)
> I get a message:

What two remarked lines? The blank ones? I removed all the semi-colons here and 
it works, although this is UAE so the timings are not exact, and it is a lot 
more forgiving of poking and peeking to the wrong places.

> guru - line 1111 emulator
> 
> ok / ok
> 
> What does it mean?

Can't remember. I even got a list of guru numbers and it doesn't say anything 
else. I think you normally get it in Blitz when there has been some sort of 
memory trashing, or stack corruption.

I'm not sure what your program is doing (presumably setting and checking the 
RTC), but I've attached a function which might help you a bit. It reads the RTC 
time and then fills in a structure so that you can read days and things.


-- 
