@NODE "Mail_40" " Re: can anyone explain this problem? "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 10-26-00 10:46:18
Subject: @{b}Re: can anyone explain this problem?@{ub}

Statement GetClockData{*cd.ClockData}
    DEFTYPE.l       sec             ; Seconds elapsed since 1-Jan-1970 from Amigas clock
    DEFTYPE.l       battclock       ; Pointer to the clock resource
    DEFTYPE.Library *UtilityBase    ; Pointer to the base of the utility library (Amiga2Date_ doesn't tokenise properly)

    sec = 0: battclock = 0: *UtilityBase = 0

    battclock = OpenResource_("battclock.resource")
    If battclock
        ; sec = ReadBattClock_
        MOVE.l a6,-(a7)
        MOVE.l -12(a4),a6
        JSR -12(a6)
        MOVE.l d0,-8(a4)
        MOVE.l (a7)+,a6

        *UtilityBase = OpenLibrary_("utility.library",0)
        If *UtilityBase
            ; Amiga2Date_ sec,*cd
            MOVE.l a6,-(a7)
            MOVE.l -8(a4),d0
            MOVE.l -4(a4),a0
            MOVE.l -16(a4),a6
            JSR -120(a6)
            MOVE.l (a7)+,a6
            CloseLibrary_ *UtilityBase
            *UtilityBase = 0
        End If
    End If
End Statement


DEFTYPE.ClockData cd
GetClockData{&cd}

NPrint cd\mday," day of the ",cd\month," month of the year ",cd\year
End


@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_41" " Re: can anyone explain this problem? "
From: Peter Thor <pettho-0@student.luth.se>
Date: 10-26-00 13:25:50
Subject: @{b}Re: can anyone explain this problem?@{ub}

 
> I am making progress with the RTC problem.
> 
> Now I have a problem with using this bit of code.
> 
> guru - line 1111 emulator

Well, I dont know what the topic was, so I'll just do some mumbling =)

Well, what's happened is that an Exception has occoured, that means
something is very wrong :)

One exception takes place when you try and divide something with Zero, Zero
device exception or if you're trying to access some odd memory-adress,
examples:
(hope you know some asm)

sub.w    d0,d0  ;clear d0
divu       d0,d3  ;try to devide with zero, thus an exception is occoured

;-- another one, failes on the 68000

lea    somemem,a3
move.b   (a3)+,d0 ; moving contents of a3 to d0,
                              ; and adding 1 to where a3 is pointing too
move.l    (a3)+,d1  ; BLAM, an adress exception takes place (68000), it's an
odd adress.

;--

An exception is basically about the processor being able to execute some
code that handles the exception in question and afterwards continues the
program at the following instruction as normal.

However, the exception you're getting I'm not really sure about, cus I don't
really know what it informs about. Blitz tend to give me that exception
sometimes (I've had it a few times) so i donno.

What machine have you got? I belive, but I'm not sure, the processor might
be trying to execute a unsupported opcode, kinda like trying to execute a
command possibly fitted on an FPU when you might be sitting without an FPU.

So, not got an FPU maybe, what CPU? It works alright here on this A4040 I'm
running on right now, tried to fiddle with the code but never got the error.

However, your code looks to have nothing but the original commands in Blitz
so I can't see what is happening, caching issues maybe... try flushing the
cache with CacheClearU() before you run it.

Anyway, I don't know what you're trying to do (didnt follow the discussion)
guess you're peeking data from somewhere:

address.l = 14417920 equals $DC0000 

which on the a500 and a3000 are reserved memorypositions, dont know about
the AGA machines though, so I guess you're fiddeling around with DMA, so,
this can require an instruction cache update.

(look up the autodocs CacheClearE() and CacheClearU() for more explanations)

Well, hope you got some of my ramblings, feel well,

//Thor
-- 
_Peter Thor_, Amiga Programmer
thor@pagan-games.com
IRC: Joru
ICQ: 11277616

@ENDNODE

