@NODE "Mail_53" " Re: DLL "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 10-18-00 10:28:45
Subject: @{b}Re: DLL@{ub}

Hi amorel

> I`m sorry to say and I appreciate the work done in it, but working with the DLL
> functions with listviews and multiple lists is a royal pain in the ass :-)

Could be worse :) http://mindprod.com/unmain.html

> Could someone send me code how to copy 2(or more) lists to 2(or an equal
> amount more) other lists in the same loop, like:
> 
> while not end of list
>    x=readitem list 1
>    y=readitem list 2
>    additem list3=x
>    additem list4=y
> wend

You better make sure that both of the lists you are copying from (lists 1 and 
2) are the same length!

Surely something like this would work (assuming you have #DLL_TRAP_ERRORS set 
to 0 and your lists are already set up):

; Two lists
RESET_LIST{*fromlist1}
RESET_LIST{*fromlist2}
; You might also need to reset the lists you are copying to
While NEXT_ITEM{*fromlist1}
    NEXT_ITEM{*fromlist2}
    ; All other lists that you want to copy from should have a NEXT_ITEM here

    ; This is where it gets messy. The way I have done it, you need to nest
    ; all the calls to ADD_ITEM for each list you want to copy to. If the call
    ; fails you should kill the items in the lists you have already created a
    ; new item for.
    If ADD_ITEM{*tolist1, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList3}
        If ADD_ITEM{*tolist2, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList4}
            *tolist1\somedata = *fromlist1\somedata
            *tolist2\otherdata = *fromlist2\otherdata
            ; repeat for all the other lists you want to copy froom and to
            ; repeat for all the other fields in your newtypes, except the
            ; <whatever>.dll field
        Else
            KILL_ITEM{*tolist1}
        End If
    End If
Wend


; Three lists
RESET_LIST{*fromlist1}
RESET_LIST{*fromlist2}
RESET_LIST{*fromlist3}
; You might also need to reset the lists you are copying to
While NEXT_ITEM{*fromlist1}
    NEXT_ITEM{*fromlist2}
    NEXT_ITEM{*fromlist3}
    ; All other lists that you want to copy from should have a NEXT_ITEM here

    ; This is where it gets messy. The way I have done it, you need to nest
    ; all the calls to ADD_ITEM for each list you want to copy to. If the call
    ; fails you should kill the items in the lists you have already created a
    ; new item for.
    If ADD_ITEM{*tolist1, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList3}
        If ADD_ITEM{*tolist2, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList4}
            If ADD_ITEM{*tolist3, sizeof.blahblahblah}
                *tolist1\somedata = *fromlist1\somedata
                *tolist2\otherdata = *fromlist2\otherdata
                *tolist3\blahdata = *fromlist3\blahdata
                ; repeat for all the other lists you want to copy froom and to
                ; repeat for all the other fields in your newtypes, except the
                ; <whatever>.dll field
            Else
                KILL_ITEM{*tolist2}
                KILL_ITEM{*tolist1}
            End If
        Else
            KILL_ITEM{*tolist1}
        End If
    End If
Wend


> There is just no clear description and example on how to do that. I can make it
> work with listviews, but I heard there was some bug or so?

The bug with listviews was actually due to a bug in the GTLib. Commands like 
GT(G|S)etAttrs and GTGadPtr did not work with listviews (and you need them when 
using DLL with GTListviews). However, I fixed this in the latest release of the 
GTLib, I'm sure I sent it to the list as well as uploaded it to Aminet and b2k.


-- 
