@NODE "Mail_58" " Re: DLL "
From: David McMinn <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Date: 10-20-00 04:14:52
Subject: @{b}Re: DLL@{ub}

Hi Amorel,

I'm sure Tony or Dave will correct me if I get something wrong. I hope so 
anyway :) Sorry I can't check any of this stuff now, not near my Amiga or 
UAE.

> DEFTYPE .myitem *myitemptr

I think this is the only real problem with your DLL setup. Any others are 
probably caused by this one.

These things are supposed to be the current item in a list. You should 
really have one of these per list I think. It makes a lot of tasks 
easier, especially when you are working with >1 list at the same time as 
you are.

So if we create a few more of them, for all the other lists, and then use 
these new current items only with a single list, your DLL setup will look 
something like this.

;This part sets up stuff to work with DLL
NEWTYPE .myitem
  node.dll
  viewlst.w
  entry$
  A.l
End NEWTYPE

Dim List dommy.w(0)

; Define current items for each list
DEFTYPE .myitem *playlst_cur
DEFTYPE .myitem *playlijst
DEFTYPE .myitem *playname
DEFTYPE .myitem *lijsttemp
DEFTYPE .myitem *nametemp

*playlst.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*playlst_cur,SizeOf .myitem}
*playlst_cur\viewlst=-1,"",-1
SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*playlst}

*playlijst.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*playlijst_cur,SizeOf .myitem}
*playlijst_cur\viewlst=-1,"",-1
SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*playlijst}

*playname.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*playname_cur,SizeOf .myitem}
*playname_cur\viewlst=-1,"",-1
SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*playname}

*lijsttemp.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*lijsttemp_cur,SizeOf .myitem}
*lijsttemp_cur\viewlst=-1,"",-1
SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*lijsttemp}

*nametemp.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*nametemp_cur,SizeOf .myitem}
*nametemp_cur\viewlst=-1,"",-1
SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*nametemp}
;End of DLL setup


> Hm, from what I could understand from the docs the *tolist1\somedata part
> is always the same name. And you point the list you are working with to
> that one.
> 
> Like *generallist=*listone

No, I think this is mentioned (a lot) in the docs as one of the 
advantages of DLL. It is so you can have 1 routine which can work on any 
list. The way it works is you write your routine with the variable name 
(e.g. *generallist). You can then point the list you want to work with 
using:
  *generallist = *listone
You never assign the *myitemptr to a list pointer (e.g. *listone). They 
are two different things, one stores one single item and the other stores 
the header information for the list.

If you were using Blitz lists, you would have to copy and paste the same 
routine for every list you wanted to use it with.

So it does not always need to be the same name.


> So to copy from 1 to another you do:
> (My actual code here, copying one list to another) Seems to not work.

It's probably due to the problem mentioned above. I've recoded it to use 
the current items which are separate for each list. However, I just 
noticed that this is probably going to end up the same as the way you had 
it, unless there is some internal issues with DLL that cause the current 
item to be "lost" (which it does at some commands).

RESET_LIST{*playlijst}
CLEAR_LIST{*lijsttemp}
While NEXT_ITEM{*playlijst}
  ADD_ITEM{*lijsttemp, SizeOf .myitem}
  *lijsttemp_cur\entry = *playlijst_cur\entry
Wend


> This works, but I HAD to insert resultprev.b=PREV_ITEM{*playlijst} or it
> would make the playlijst list twice as long with every other item being
> one from the playname list :-} It seems like any additem of any list adds
> an item to the other list as well.

Hmm, that sounds like something that could happen if you are only using 1 
current item variable. Try it using one current item variable for each 
list (your code is below, re-written for that).

      ; You must put the GTChangeList to remove the DLL from the listview
      ; before you modify the DLL. This is exactly the same as with Blitz
      ; lists - you must detach the list before modifying the list
      GTChangeList whichgtlist.b,30
      CLEAR_LIST{*playlijst}
      CLEAR_LIST{*playname}
      tel.l=0
      randomcount.l=0
      ; Not sure about the way you have opened files. I'm sure you do
      ; not need both calls, but just ReadFile
      If ReadFile(1,listname$)
          FileInput 1
          dummy$=Edit$(192)
          While NOT Eof(1)
              dummy2$=Edit$(192)
              ADD_ITEM{*playlijst,SizeOf .myitem}
              *playlijst_cur\entry = dummy2$
              *playlijst_cur\A=tel.l
              ADD_ITEM{*playname, SizeOf .myitem}
              *playname_cur\entry=GetFileName(dummy2$)
              *playname_cur\A=tel.l
              tel.l=tel.l+1
              randomcount.l=randomcount.l+1
          Wend
          playlistexist.b=1
          succesloadlist.b=1
          firsttime.b=False
          PopInput
          CloseFile 1
      EndIf
      GTSetAttrs whichgtlist.b,30,#GTLV_Labels,*playname


> *myitemptr just seems to be a general name pointing to whichever list
> you`re  
> 
> working with currently. To change to another list you have to do
> *myitemptr=*otherlist I read you got to do some additional coding if the
> list pointer changes before you change to another list, but the docs
> didn`t really make it clear how to do that.

*myitemptr is supposed to be a current item pointer. I don't think it's 
made clear in the docs, but I think there should be a separate one of 
these for each list.

If you do need to fix the current item pointer for some reason I think 
you do something like:
  *myitemptr = GET_CURRENT_ITEM{*mylist}

But like you, I'm not sure when you need it. I think it tells you in the 
descriptions of the DLL functions when you need to call this afterwards.

> BY the way, it is best to keep all names the same in all docs and
> examples. That might already clear up things.
>
> Can you understand why I hate working with pointers? It`s not compatible
> with a human brain :-}

It's the common problem of a doc<->brain<->pointer incompatibility. Lucky 
you're not a PC, you'd have to upgrade your brain to run Windows 2000 ;)


Just seen your other mail to the list, I'll try to clarify.

You have a DLL list, called something like *mylist. This contains 
information about the internals of the DLL, and needs to be passed as a 
parameter to most/all DLL functions. This is how you control what list 
gets operated on.

You also need a current item for the list, such as *mylistptr. I think 
there should be one of these for each list. Using this is how you access 
the variables in each item of the DLL. This is completely separate from 
*mylist.


|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| c |\/| ][ |\| |\|  | dave@satanicdreams.com
http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn     | ICQ=16827694
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_59" " Re: DLL "
From: Tony Rolfe <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Date: 10-21-00 03:08:10
Subject: @{b}Re: DLL@{ub}

On Fri, 20 Oct 2000 05:14:52 +0100 David McMinn said:
> Hi Amorel,
> 
> I'm sure Tony or Dave will correct me if I get something wrong. I hope so 
> anyway :) Sorry I can't check any of this stuff now, not near my Amiga or 
> UAE.

Yep... You've got it exactly right.    There MUST be one current item
pointer for each list.    This MUST be set up in the way you described
below.

The only exception to this is that the "Dummy" list used in a common
routine must have a corresponding "Dummy" item, but that list and item
MUST NOT be initialised with the INIT_LIST.

To use the Dummy List you simply  do a

*DummyList = *OneOfTheRealLists

and then every time the common routine wants to use the current item
it must do a GET_CURRENT_ITEM{*DummyList}

I take Amorel's point that the Docs should be consistemt in use of
names.   The only excuse is that they were a combination of Dave's and
my naming conventions.   I'll try to get round to updating them soon.

The simplest way to be safe is to use a naming convention like:
*PlayList  for the List and *PlayItem for the Item.     You then call
every function using the List name (Except for IntiList - should I
change that??  Dave set it up that way originally and I've never
thought to change it.)

Hope that David's explanation makes things a bit clearer.    Remember
that a pointer is just a longword containing an address, not a cunning
plan to rot our brains (although sometimes it does seem like that)

Cheers

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+8Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater
ICQ #51271965
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_60" " Re: DLL "
From: Tony Rolfe <edgewater@shoalhaven.net.au>
Date: 10-21-00 03:27:47
Subject: @{b}Re: DLL@{ub}

On Fri, 20 Oct 2000 04:11:45 GMT+5DST amorel said:
> On 18-Oct, Tony Rolfe wrote:
> C=I'm not really sure what you are trying to achieve, but...
> 
> Other email(s) I sent after this one should explain it more.
> 
> Well, the way the dll example does add an item to a list is this(including
> some relevant setup):
> 
> NEWTYPE .bumitem
>   node.dll
>   pad.w
>   string.s
>   number.w
>   dude.s
>   quick.q
>   word.s
>   etc.b
>   pad1.b
> End NEWTYPE
> 
> DEFTYPE .bumitem *myitem
> 
> *mylist.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*myitem,SizeOf .bumitem}
> 
> *myitem\pad=-1,"",-1,"",-1,"",-1,-1
> 
> SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*mylist}
> 
> For loop=1 To 10
> 
>   ADD_ITEM{*mylist,SizeOf .bumitem}      ;must pass the sizeof your item to
> add to the list
Yep, I always forget that, but the compiler reminds me :-(
> 
>   *myitem\number=loop
> 
> Next loop
> 
> Here *myitem is NOT the name of the list. The list is called *mylist.
> Lets assume there r 2 lists in this example and you want to fill both. This
> way will not work:
> 
> For loop=1 To 10
> 
>   ADD_ITEM{*mylist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *myitem\number=loop
>   ADD_ITEM{*mysecondlist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *myitem\numbersecondlist=loop
> 
> Next loop

That's because you are using the same item for two lists.

You need to do two INIT_LIST commands (one for each list) and use a
different item for each (*FirstItem for *FirstList and *SecondItem for
*SecondList)

You are right that the documentation doesn't make that clear, so I'll
fix it up ASAP)
> 
> Or this, it will not work either:
> 
> For loop=1 To 10
> 
>   ADD_ITEM{*mylist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *mylist\number=loop
>   ADD_ITEM{*mysecondlist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *mysecondlist\numbersecondlist=loop
> 
> Next loop

That's because you are using the list manes for the item names.
> 
> And this won`t work either:
> 
> For loop=1 To 10
> 
>   ADD_ITEM{*mylist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   ADD_ITEM{*mysecondlist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *mylist\number=loop
>   *mysecondlist\numbersecondlist=loop
> 
> Next loop

Same as above
> 
> So how did David come up with a similar example?
> 
> C=    If ADD_ITEM{*tolist1, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList3}
> C=        If ADD_ITEM{*tolist2, sizeof.TheTypeForItemsInList4}
> C=            *tolist1\somedata = *fromlist1\somedata
> C=            *tolist2\otherdata = *fromlist2\otherdata
> 
> Admitted, this is copying from 1 list to another, but the problem
> remains the same.

Dave's example here is also wrong.   He is using the list names
instead of the item names.

The thing to remember is that the list name addresses the list header
and the item name addresses your data.    Imagine a queue of people
waiting for a teller in the bank.     The Teller is the list name, the
item addresses one of the people in the queue.    As you change the
item address (by NEXT_ITEM for example, you are merely pointing at a
different person in the queue).    Lousy analogy I know, but the best
I can come up with in a hurry.

Your data is always accessed by *ItemName\FieldNameInNewType
So,  you need to do:
 
 NEWTYPE .bumitem
   node.dll
   pad.w
   string.s
   number.w
   dude.s
   quick.q
   word.s
   etc.b
   pad1.b
 End NEWTYPE

 DEFTYPE .bumitem *myitem, *myseconditem
 
 *mylist.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*myitem,SizeOf .bumitem}
 *myitem\pad=-1,"",-1,"",-1,"",-1,-1
 SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*mylist}

 *mysecondlist.dllhead=INIT_LIST{&*myseconditem,SizeOf .bumitem}
 *myseconditem\pad=-1,"",-1,"",-1,"",-1,-1
 SET_STRING_POSITIONS{*mysecondlist}
  
 For loop=1 To 10
> 
>   ADD_ITEM{*mylist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   ADD_ITEM{*mysecondlist,SizeOf .bumitem}
>   *myitemt\number=loop
>   *myseconditem\number=loop
> 
> Next loop

If you then want to copy the data  from *mylist to *mythirdlist, you
would have to define *mythirditem and initialise *mythirdlist

Hope that clarifies things a bit.

Cheers

-- 
Tony Rolfe
Amiga 2000, 68030/25, 1+8Mb
www.shoalhaven.net.au/edgewater
ICQ #51271965
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_61" " Re: DLL "
