@NODE "Mail_68" " Idea for program "
From: KristianGK@aol.com
Date: 10-29-00 17:47:14
Subject: @{b}Idea for program@{ub}

Hi,

I find it incredibly irritating when I run some software and it crashes. It 
is perhaps more annoying when I find that by simply turning off the caches, 
the program will run perfectly.

What about a program that checks to code for illegal instructions before 
executing it??
Then... no more nasty gurus for old software.

What do you think?

Kris,
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_69" " Re: Idea for program "
From: Ralf Berkvens <ralf@ilse.nl>
Date: 10-30-00 07:49:51
Subject: @{b}Re: Idea for program@{ub}

> Hi,
> 
> I find it incredibly irritating when I run some software and it crashes. It 
> is perhaps more annoying when I find that by simply turning off the caches, 
> the program will run perfectly.
> 
> What about a program that checks to code for illegal instructions before 
> executing it??
> Then... no more nasty gurus for old software.
> 
> What do you think?
> 
> Kris,
> 
My question would be: what is an illegal instruction when speaking about
memory/instruction cache?

I wrote an assembler program once that had the following code in it:

move.b <someaddress>, 0
....
move.b 0, <someotheraddress>

This is not illegal (byte 0 in the memory is generally free, because it
		holds the last guru number), but with data-chaches on, it will not work
if for example you read the byte from a sampler. 

Ralf

