@NODE "Mail_70" " Re: Idea for program "
From: Sami Nõõtõnen <sami.naatanen@dlc.fi>
Date: 10-30-00 08:12:42
Subject: @{b}Re: Idea for program@{ub}



Ralf Berkvens wrote:

> My question would be: what is an illegal instruction when speaking about
> memory/instruction cache?
> 
> I wrote an assembler program once that had the following code in it:
> 
> move.b <someaddress>, 0
> ....
> move.b 0, <someotheraddress>
> 
> This is not illegal (byte 0 in the memory is generally free, because it
>                 holds the last guru number), but with data-chaches on, it will not work
> if for example you read the byte from a sampler.

Well it is an illegal address, because you does not own it. It's the
system autovector call address!!!

And why would you want to use that address? Why not using you own
memory.
(Dynamically allocated or statically allocated ie within the executable
file)

I don't know why your sampling program didn't work, but the Custom chip
addresses are all non cacheable,
so you shouldn't have had any problems.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_71" " Re: Idea for program "
From: Ralf Berkvens <ralf@ilse.nl>
Date: 10-30-00 08:20:19
Subject: @{b}Re: Idea for program@{ub}

> Well it is an illegal address, because you does not own it. It's the
> system autovector call address!!!
That the biggest problem with the amiga.. Nobody 'owns' memory space.
You can reserve it for use, but anyone else who wants to can simple
abuse it aswell without generating errors on their part.
> 
> And why would you want to use that address? Why not using you own
> memory.
My brother thought this up (he used to be an assembly whiz (made at least
			one demo which was rather good :)), and it seemed handy at the time :P
Obviously i have no idea WHY he actually used address 0 (and 1).
> (Dynamically allocated or statically allocated ie within the executable
> file)
> 
> I don't know why your sampling program didn't work, but the Custom chip
> addresses are all non cacheable,
> so you shouldn't have had any problems.
Scary :) I had to flush the caches everytime (otherwise i got a line signal
	at only one level.).

Ralf
