Subject: @{b}Re: JSR's@{ub}

On Sat, 14 Oct 2000 06:41:38 -0700 Curt Esser said:
> 
> But, why not just convert the subroutine into a function?  (or statement)
> Have the converted subroutine Share all the necessary variables and it will
> still work exactly the same.

There is a reason, a bit hard to explain though, but I'll try...

I've got a common routine which does things to a specified DLL List.  
Each calling routine needs to do some specific stuff at a certain
point.   At the moment, each calling routine gosub's the common
routine having set the address of it's specific routine in a variable.
The common routine then does a JSR to the specific routine which does
it's stuff and RTS's back.

Now...    This common routine is completely integrated into my
MotelManager (uses variables set up elsewhere in the program and NEEDS
the MM support routines to function.    I'm trying to surgically
remove this from MM so I can use it elsewhere and I thought the best
way would be to convert it to functions rather than gosubs, so I can
control the variables it uses (If I don't share them I can't affect
the outside world).

Hence the question, will the JSR stuff still work in a function?

Can't see a way to build a function name on the fly - but the ASM
Guru's here will probably tell me how :-)

Cheers


