@NODE "Mail_155" " Stack size. "
From: "A. Timiney" <een0a2t@ECU-01.NOVELL.LEEDS.AC.UK>
Date: 10-16-00 08:24:24
Subject: @{b}Stack size.@{ub}

Hi,
 I cant debug my latest program because the debugger tells me I'm 
out of stack space. I can get around this by compiling it and 
running it from shell with a bigger stack.... but, of course, I cant 
debug it now.
Can someone offer a solution (like, will increasing Blitz's stack sive 
cause it to run my program with a larger stack, or is there a way of 
increasing the default stack size, or can I run the debugger with a 
compiled program outside blitz, or can I free up some unused 
variables, or am I screwed?)

Thanks,
-Alex Timiney
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Mail_156" " Re: Stack size. "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 10-16-00 10:26:22
Subject: @{b}Re: Stack size.@{ub}

> Can someone offer a solution (like, will increasing Blitz's stack sive 
> cause it to run my program with a larger stack, or is there a way of 
> increasing the default stack size, or can I run the debugger with a 
> compiled program outside blitz, or can I free up some unused 
> variables, or am I screwed?)

If you increase Blitz's stack before you run it, you do get a bigger stack to 
play with. This also affects the stack that your program gets. I don't think 
the debugger can have it's stack set separately.

You could also try a program like StackAttack. Not sure what it does, but I 
know it helps when OS programs and the like run out of stack - perhaps it 
intercepts low stack memory and dynamically increases it, or it looks for a 
task name when it gets run and then increases the stack then. If it's something 
like those two, you could get it to increase the stack for Blitz, the debugger 
and your program (assuming changing the Blitz2 stack doesn't work).

As for code things you can do, you could try increasing the stack from inside 
your program. Either check out the OS StackSwap_ command, or get the MUI2.res 
which has macros which can call this function for you. You could also try 
eliminating local variables that you do not need, and if your program is 
recursing see if you can decrease the recursion depth. Even calling functions 
from within functions from within functions, although not the same as 
recursion, will have the same effect on stack usage, so you could try 
eliminating code like that.


-- 
